`crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/` is the orchestration core of a `ctx-cage` invocation: it sequences prepare → run → teardown for one sandboxed subprocess run and exposes the crate's real entry point, `execute(&Resolved) -> Result<i32, CageError>`. Depending on this subtree gets you a fully-provisioned, executed, and cleaned-up `bwrap` cage; callers never touch `bwrap`, proxy sockets, or run-dir paths directly.

Data flows in one direction: `prepare::prepare_run` builds `Prep` (rundir path, rules file, mask file, optional claude runtime) from `Resolved`; the run phase consumes `Prep` to construct the `bwrap` invocation and environment; `teardown::teardown_run` then deletes exactly `prep.rundir` and nothing else, unconditionally and without observable failure, even if the run phase errored. `mode_is_billed(&r.mode)` (from `crate::cli`) is checked independently in both `prepare` (to gate on a clean git tree and resolve a claude runtime) and the run phase (to decide whether to start networking); a change to which modes count as billed must be checked against both sites. The rules file path (`prep.rules_file`, sourced from `CAGE_RULES_MD`) and the mask file written by `prepare` are consumed by the run phase's `bwrap` config and system-prompt injection — changing what `prepare` writes changes what gets mounted/appended in the run phase.

There are two independently-maintained phase-2 implementations: `run.rs` (`run_until_exit`, wired into `mod.rs` per its own notes) runs an API-proxy model where the caged claude's OAuth header passes straight through a Unix-socket proxy (`ProxyConfig.api_key` always `None`), while `serve.rs` (`serve_until_exit`) runs a broker model instead, allowlisting only `ctx-access`/`ctx-verify` over a similarly-named Unix socket. `mod.rs`'s own edit notes list only `prepare.rs`/`run.rs`/`teardown.rs` as the phases it sequences, not `serve.rs` — an editor touching phase-2 behavior must confirm which of `run.rs` or `serve.rs` is actually invoked before assuming a change takes effect.

`teardown.rs`'s scope invariant (never touch anything outside `prep.rundir`) and its silence on error are the only guarantees the rest of the crate can rely on for cleanup; nothing in `run.rs`/`serve.rs` performs its own socket-file removal beyond what teardown or their own stop/join sequences handle at exit.